---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema, medicalWebPageSchema } from '../../../../data/schema.js';

const title = '1–3 Month Milestones: What to Expect and Signs of Progress';
const description = 'Between 1 and 3 months, babies reach major developmental milestones including social smiles, improved head control, cooing, and reacting to their environment — based on current CDC and AAP milestone checklists.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'When should I expect my baby\'s first real smile?',
    answer: 'The first "social smile" — a smile in response to your voice or face — typically appears between 6 and 8 weeks of age, according to the CDC milestone checklist (2022). This is a major milestone in social and emotional development. If your baby is not smiling socially by 3 months, discuss it with your pediatrician.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should my baby be holding their head up by 3 months?',
    answer: 'By 2 months, most babies can hold their head up when pushing up on their tummy. By 3–4 months, head control becomes much steadier. The CDC lists holding the head up during tummy time as a milestone by 4 months. Tummy time is the most effective way to build the neck and shoulder muscles needed for this skill (CDC, 2022).',
  },
  {
    question: 'What sounds should a 2-month-old make?',
    answer: 'By 2 months, babies begin making sounds other than crying. You will hear cooing — vowel sounds like "ooh" and "ah" — and gurgling. They also react to loud sounds by startling or becoming quiet (CDC, 2022). These sounds are your baby\'s first intentional social communication.',
  },
];

const aSchema = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/1-3-months/milestones/',
});
const fSchema = faqSchema(faqs);
const mSchema = medicalWebPageSchema({
  name: title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/1-3-months/milestones/',
});
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  articleSchema={aSchema}
  faqSchema={fSchema}
  medicalSchema={mSchema}
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: '1–3 Months', href: '/ages/1-3-months/' },
    { label: 'Milestones' },
  ]}
>
  <h1>1–3 Month Milestones: What to Expect</h1>

  <p>The transition from the newborn phase into early infancy (1–3 months) brings a dramatic increase in alertness. Your baby is beginning to wake up to the world — recognizing familiar faces, communicating with more than just tears, and building the physical strength that will drive the motor milestones to come.</p>

  <p>Developmental milestones are behaviors and physical skills seen in infants as they grow. While every child develops at their own pace, the CDC and AAP provide general timeframes for when most children reach certain milestones.</p>

  <h2>What social and emotional milestones should I look for at 1–3 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 2 months, most babies smile in response to your face or voice (the social smile), watch your face attentively, and begin to show signs of brief self-soothing by bringing their hands to their mouth (CDC, 2022). These social behaviors indicate your baby is beginning to form the attachment relationship that underpins all future emotional development.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Social smile:</strong> They smile at you when you talk to or smile at them — the most celebrated milestone of this stage.</li>
    <li><strong>Alertness:</strong> They look at your face and watch you as you move around the room.</li>
    <li><strong>Self-soothing:</strong> They may briefly calm themselves by bringing their hands to their mouth and sucking on them.</li>
    <li><strong>Recognition:</strong> They seem happy to see familiar faces, especially parents and regular caregivers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What communication milestones should my 1–3 month old reach?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 2 months, most babies produce cooing sounds — vowel-heavy vocalizations like "ooh" and "ah" — and begin turning their head toward the sound of a familiar voice (CDC, 2022). These sounds are your baby's first intentional social communication. They are practicing the back-and-forth turn-taking that forms the foundation of all language development.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cooing:</strong> They make gurgling or vowel sounds in addition to crying.</li>
    <li><strong>Turning toward sounds:</strong> They may turn their head toward the sound of your voice.</li>
    <li><strong>Reacting to environment:</strong> They react to loud sounds by startling or looking toward the source.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What cognitive milestones should I expect at 1–3 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 2 months, most babies can visually follow a slowly moving object across their field of vision, look at a toy for several seconds when held nearby, and begin to recognize familiar faces from a distance (CDC, 2022). These cognitive gains reflect the rapid development of visual cortex function and early memory formation during this period.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Visual tracking:</strong> They follow moving objects with their eyes — a toy, your face, a brightly colored mobile.</li>
    <li><strong>Sustained focus:</strong> They look at a toy for several seconds when held in front of them.</li>
    <li><strong>Face recognition:</strong> They begin to distinguish familiar people from strangers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What physical and motor milestones should my baby hit at 1–3 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">By 2 months, most babies can hold their head up briefly while on their tummy and move both arms and both legs symmetrically (CDC, 2022). By 3 months, head control improves significantly, and many babies begin pushing up onto their forearms during tummy time. Daily supervised tummy time is the most effective way to build these muscles.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Head control:</strong> They can hold their head up and begin to push up when lying on their tummy.</li>
    <li><strong>Hand movements:</strong> They open their hands briefly and may bring them to their mouth.</li>
    <li><strong>Symmetry:</strong> They move both arms and both legs. If you notice one side moving significantly less than the other, mention it to your pediatrician.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Common Questions About 1–3 Month Milestones</h2>
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-question">{faq.question}</p>
        <p class="faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>When should I talk to my pediatrician about my baby's milestones?</h2>
    <p>The CDC and AAP recommend discussing your baby's development at every well-child visit. Talk to your pediatrician if your 2-month-old:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Does not respond to loud sounds</li>
      <li>Does not watch things as they move</li>
      <li>Does not smile at people</li>
      <li>Does not bring hands to mouth</li>
      <li>Cannot hold their head up when pushing up on their tummy</li>
      <li>Has lost skills they once had</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Early identification leads to earlier support, and outcomes are consistently better when concerns are addressed promptly. If something feels off, call your pediatrician — don't wait for the next scheduled visit.</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
